{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>A number of polypeptidic hormones, mainly expressed in the intestine or the pancreas, belong to a group of structurally related peptides [[cite:PUB00000024], [cite:PUB00000025]]. Once such hormone, glucagon is widely distributed and produced in the alpha-cells of pancreatic islets [[cite:PUB00001745]]. It affects glucose metabolism in the liver [[cite:PUB00004603]] by inhibiting glycogen synthesis, stimulating glycogenolysis and enhancing gluconeogenesis. It also increases mobilisation of glucose, free fatty acids and ketone bodies, which are metabolites produced in excess in diabetes mellitus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Glucagon is produced, like other peptide hormones, as part of a larger precursor (preproglucagon), which is cleaved to produce glucagon, glucagon-like protein I (GLP-1) and glucagon-like protein II (GLP-2) [[cite:PUB00002491]]. GLP-1 and GLP-2 are key neuroendocrine signals for the gut-brain axis to control food intake and glucose homeostasis [[cite:PUB00088953]]. The structure of glucagon itself is fully conserved in all known mammalian species [[cite:PUB00001745]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "6phi", "name" "Crystal structure of native glucagon in space group I41 at 1.1 A resolution"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR11418" "GLUCAGON"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Glucagon", "short" "Glucagon"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 53, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 603, "taxa" 2185, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1239, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1239, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 891}, "pathways" 40}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"gp" {"displayName" "Genome Properties", "description" "Genome properties is an annotation system whereby functional attributes can be assigned to a genome, based on the presence of a defined set of pr